  Many important practical markets inherently involve the interaction of
strategic buyers with strategic sellers. A fundamental impossibility result for
such two-sided markets due to Myerson and Satterthwaite establishes that even
in the simplest such market, that of bilateral trade, it is impossible to
design a mechanism that is individually rational, truthful, (weakly) budget
balanced, and efficient. Even worse, it is known that the "second best"
mechanism$-$the mechanism that maximizes social welfare subject to the other
constraints$-$has to be carefully tailored to the Bayesian priors and is
extremely complex.
